{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{COI|date=November 2017}} {{EngvarB|date=February 2018}} {{Infobox judge | honorific-prefix = [[His Honour]] Judge | name = Martin Beddoe | honorific-suffix = | image = Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (HM Government).svg | alt = | caption = | image_size = 300px | office1 = [[Circuit judge (England and Wales)|Circuit judge]] | term_start1 = 2007 | term_end1 = | nominator1 = | appointer1 = [[Elizabeth II]] | predecessor1 = | successor1 = | order2 = | office2 = [[Recorder (judge)|Crown Court Recorder]] | term_start2 = 2002 | term_end2 = 2007 | predecessor2 = | successor2 = | office3 = Standing Counsel to [[HM Revenue and Customs]] | term_start3 = 2005 | term_end3 = 2007 | predecessor3 = | successor3 = | birth_name = Martin William Denton Beddoe | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1955|7|7}} | birth_place = Abyad, [[Egypt]]<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk"/> | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_co-ordinates = | citizenship = | nationality = British | party = | otherparty = | spouse = [[Mary Margaret Anne McCabe]]<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk"/> | partner = | relations = | children = Poppy | parents = Lieutenant Colonel Arthur Beddoe, Jane Beddoe<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk"/> | residence = London, United Kingdom | education = [[Tonbridge School]] | alma_mater = BA Hons, [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]] | occupation = Judge, member of the Parole Board of England & Wales<ref name="“www.gov.uk"/> | profession = | known_for = Presiding over high profie criminal cases | cabinet = | committees = | portfolio = | religion = | awards = | interests = | data1 = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | recreation = Royal Worlington and Newmarket Golf; Philanderers Cricket. | module3 = | module4 = | module5 = | footnotes = }}
His Honour Judge '''Martin William Denton Beddoe''' (born 7 July 1955) is a British [[Circuit judge (England and Wales)|judge]]<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Who's Who 2009: New Names |url=http://i.telegraph.co.uk/telegraph/multimedia/archive/01123/Who_s_Who_new_name_1123303a.pdf |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> known for having presided over many high-profile criminal cases.<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk"/> He is a former Crown Court Recorder,<ref name="“the lawgazette.co.uk">{{cite news |title=The Law Gazette: Official Public Record |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/L-56455-1002 |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> member of the [[Parole Board of England and Wales]]<ref name="“www.gov.uk">{{cite news |title=Parole Board of England and Wales |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/notice-of-re-appointments-to-the-parole-board |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> and a tutor judge of the [[Judicial College]].<ref name="“gov.uk03">{{cite news |title=Parole Board members |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/247243/1363.pdf |accessdate=15 October 2017 |date=15 October 2017}}</ref> In March 2013 he was one of the judges appointed to hear an inquest into the death of [[Bethlem_Royal_Hospital#Fatal_restraint_on_Olaseni_Lewis|Olaseni Lewis]].<ref name="“parliament.uk">{{cite news |title=Parole Board of England and Wales |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130312/text/130312w0003.htm |accessdate=5 September 2017 |date=5 September 2017}}</ref>
==Early life== Beddoe came from a military family. He was born in Abyad, [[Egypt]],<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk"/> where his father, [[World War II]] veteran Lieutenant Colonel Arthur Beddoe<ref name="“wishful-thinking.org">{{cite news |title=WW2 Memorial Great Rissington, Gloucestershire, St John the Baptist's Churchyard |url=http://places.wishful-thinking.org.uk/GLS/GreatRissington/MIs.html |accessdate=5 September 2017 |date=5 September 2017}}</ref> was serving at the time of his birth.<ref name="“nationalarchives.gov.uk">{{cite news |title=Welsh Regiment: 1/4th Battalion |url=http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C675408 |accessdate=5 September 2017 |date=5 September 2017}}</ref> His father had a very distinguished military career and before his posting to Egypt was an infantry battalion commanding officer in [[Welsh Regiment]] during the [[Second World War]]. Judge Beddoe takes pride in his Welsh heritage.<ref name="“ww1infantrycos.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Parole Board of England and Wales |url=http://www.ww1infantrycos.co.uk/welshreg.html |accessdate=5 September 2017 |date=5 September 2017}}</ref>
==Career at the Bar== Beddoe was educated at [[Tonbridge School]] and [[Peterhouse, Cambridge]]. He was [[called to the bar]] as a member of [[Gray's Inn]] in 1979 and thereafter practised as a [[barrister]] at 36 Bedford Row chambers<ref name="“36group.co.uk">{{cite news |title=36 Bedford Row: Former Members |url=https://36group.co.uk/door-tenants-former-members |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> where he practised from 1980 specialising in [[prosecution]] work, including prosecution of several cases of fraud, [[tax evasion]], [[organised crime]] and murder, until 2005,<ref name="“www.thegovernmentsays.com">{{cite news |title=14 December 2007 Judicial Appointments |url=http://www.thegovernmentsays.com/history/2007-12-14 |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> when he was appointed Standing Counsel to the [[Revenue and Customs Prosecutions Office]].<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk"/><ref name="“lexisweb.co.uk">{{cite news |title=R v Cornfield: Martin Beddoe instructed by the Revenue and Customs Prosecutions Office for the Revenue |url=http://lexisweb.co.uk/cases/2006/october/r-v-cornfield |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> He served in that capacity until December 2007, when he was appointed circuit judge.<ref name="“www.m2.com">{{cite news |title=Appointment of a Circuit Judge – His Honour Judge Beddoe |url=http://www.m2.com/m2/web/story.php/20072A1F22F550AC51A0802573B100011AA1 |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref>
===Standing Counsel to HMRC=== Beddoe served as a Standing Counsel to the [[Revenue and Customs Prosecutions Office]] for 3 years, until December 2007, dealing with numerous high level drug importations and diversion cases, including some of the largest fraud prosecutions in the country such as the largest diversion fraud ever prosecuted at the time.<ref name="“telegraph.co.uk"/>
===Prosecutor=== Beddoe was a senior prosecutor in [[Peterborough]] Crown Court, Cambridgeshire. Throughout his career he successfully prosecuted many criminal cases including prosecution of a fraudster who was found guilty of involvement in a £1.5&nbsp;million fraud in 2002,<ref name="“worksopguardian.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Fraudster on the run|url=http://www.worksopguardian.co.uk/news/fraudster-on-the-run-1-626865 |accessdate=16 August 2017 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref> and a solicitor who plead guilty to stealing £350,000 in fees from clients in 2005.<ref name="“www.bbc.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Solicitor pleads guilty to theft |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/leicestershire/4634803.stm |accessdate=16 August 2017 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref> Solicitor Christopher McChrystal was arrested in October 2004 after the [[Law Society]] referred his case to the police.<ref name="“www.solicitorstribunal.org.uk">{{cite news |title=www.solicitorstribunal.org.uk |url=http://www.solicitorstribunal.org.uk/sites/default/files-sdt/9159-2004%20-%20McChrystal.pdf |accessdate=16 August 2017 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref> McChrystal was subsequently struck off after Lincoln Crown Court's finding that he used the clients' money to make an investment into his business.<ref name="“www.solicitorstribunal.org.uk"/> In 2003 Beddoe was a senior prosecutor in court cases resulting from Operation Harrier,<ref name="“justiceinspectorates.gov.uk">{{cite news |title=THE INSPECTORATE'S REPORT ON CPS CAMBRIDGESHIRE |url=http://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/crown-prosecution-service/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2014/04/Cambs0103Rep.pdf |accessdate=16 August 2017 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref> a clean-up operation which has declared all-out war against Class A drugs in [[Peterborough]], Cambridgeshire.<ref name="“peterboroughtoday.co.uk">{{cite news |title=A TEAM of prosecutors has moved into a city police station to deal with the mass arrests resulting from drugs crackdown Operation Harrier |url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/environment/crime-extra-lawyers-to-handle-mass-drug-arrests-1-101561|accessdate=16 August 2017 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref>
===Defence counsel=== Beddoe has defended at the criminal bar in drug cases, fraud, homicide and other serious crime.<ref name="“zoominfo">{{cite news |title=Martin Beddoe: barrister |url=https://www.zoominfo.com/p/Martin-Beddoe/636223420 |accessdate=15 October 2017 |date=15 October 2017}}</ref> He also dealt with Courts Martial, Inquests and Public Enquiries. In 2005 he successfully defended Jason Smith, British soldier who served eight years in the British Army. The court heard that Smith's successful Army career was halted prematurely due to a back injury and he had struggled to come to terms with it. In March 2005, as a result of his post-traumatic stress disorder, Smith had carried out a raid of a petrol station in Northampton at knife-point, but later dropped 45 in cash as the owner and several villagers gave chase.<ref name="“northamptonchron.co.uk">{{cite news |title=A FORMER soldier who saw active service in Bosnia and Northern Ireland has escaped a prison sentence for an armed robbery at a petrol station in a Northamptonshire village |url=http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/news/no-jail-term-after-petrol-station-raid-1-909379 |accessdate=15 October 2017 |date=15 October 2017}}</ref> Sentencing Jason Smith to a two-year suspended sentence, Judge Nigel Daly told him: {{quote|It is the first time you have been in court and you are of previous good character and here you are in relation to a very serious offence. You had considerable problems with your finances and then suffered a reactive depression brought on by the spiralling debts.<ref name="“northamptonchron.co.uk"/>}}
==Judicial career== As a judge, Beddoe has presided over many high-profile criminal cases,<ref name="“forbes01">{{cite news |title='You Sold Your Soul...For Bling And Swank': U.K. Judge Jails Former Bankers For Scam |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dinamedland/2017/02/03/you-sold-your-soul-for-bling-and-swank-u-k-judge-jails-former-bankers-for-scam/ |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref><ref name="“dailymail01">{{cite news |title=Sixth-former on work experience stole thousands from top law firm in cheque scam |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1033436/Sixth-work-experience-stole-thousands-law-firm-cheque-scam.html |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> including trial of [[BAFTA]] nominated film producers<ref name="“bbc01">{{cite news |title=Bafta-nominated producers of Starsuckers film jailed for £2.2m tax scam |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-36687365 |accessdate=16 August 2017 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref> who used Film [[Tax Credit]] to claim back inflated cash from the [[Treasury]].<ref name="“hamhigh.co.uk">{{cite news |title=Bafta-nominated Gospel Oak film producer jailed over £2.2m tax scam is ordered to repay £100,000 |url=http://www.hamhigh.co.uk/news/bafta-nominated-gospel-oak-film-producer-jailed-over-2-2m-tax-scam-is-ordered-to-repay-100-000-1-4902352 |accessdate=16 August 2017 |date=16 August 2017}}</ref>
===Judicial appointments=== {{s-start}} {{s-legal}}{{s-bef|before=Unknown}} {{s-ttl|title=[[Circuit judge (England and Wales)|Circuit Judge]] |years=2007–present}} {{s-inc|=}} {{s-end}}
[[File:Southwark Crown Court entrance.jpg|right|thumb|In 2007 His Honour Judge Beddoe became the Resident Judge on the South Eastern Circuit based at [[Southwark Crown Court]]]] Beddoe was a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]] of the [[Crown Court]] from 2002 until 2007, when he was appointed a Senior Circuit Judge,<ref name="“oxford01">{{cite news |title=Oxford Who is Who in History of Law and Procedure |url=http://oxfordindex.oup.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U246442 |accessdate=15 August 2017 |date=15 August 2017}}</ref> becoming the Resident Judge on the South Eastern Circuit based at [[Southwark Crown Court]].<ref name="“www.m2.com"/>
===Notable cases=== In 2017 Judge Beddoe presided over the case of Ricardo McFarlane, 30-year-old Muslim convert charged with anti-social behaviour after preaching [[Sharia law]] in [[Oxford Street]] and two other London venues,<ref name="“filmfast">{{cite news |title=Judge's fury at Muslim convert for refusing to stand in court |url=http://filmfast.co.uk/news/judges-fury-at-muslim-convert-for-refusing-to-stand-in-court |accessdate=2 September 2017 |date=2 September 2017}}</ref> who declined to stand up in court on religious grounds.<ref name="“telegraph06">{{cite news |title=Muslim convert accused of preaching sharia law says he won't stand for any man before getting to his feet when ordered by judge |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/29/muslim-convert-accused-preaching-sharia-law-ordered-stand-judge/ |accessdate=31 August 2017 |date=31 August 2017}}</ref> McFarlane allegedly breached the terms of an [[Asbo|antisocial behaviour order]]<ref name="“ibtimes">{{cite news |title=Judge orders Asbo preacher to stand up: 'This is not a court of religion |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/judge-orders-asbo-preacher-stand-this-not-court-religion-1637220 |accessdate=2 September 2017 |date=2 September 2017}}</ref> barring him from addressing members of the public to promote sharia law.<ref name="“thetimes01">{{cite news |title=Judge orders Asbo preacher Ricardo McFarlane to stand up in court |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/judge-orders-asbo-preacher-ricardo-mcfarlane-to-stand-up-in-court-8qxfl2pkx |accessdate=31 August 2017 |date=31 August 2017}}</ref> At the hearing in [[Southwark Crown Court]], Judge Beddoe noticed that McFarlane did not stand when he entered the room.<ref name="“metro02">{{cite news |title=You stand up in my court, judge tells sharia convert |url=https://www.metro.news/you-stand-up-in-my-court-judge-tells-sharia-convert/727402/ |accessdate=1 September 2017 |date=1 September 2017}}</ref> McFarlane's defence barrister commented: {{quote|"Because of his religious belief he believes there is only one person who he should bow to."<ref name="“Express02">{{cite news |title=Judge's fury at Muslim convert for refusing to stand in court |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/847415/Judge-fury-Muslim-convert-refusing-to-stand-in-court/amp|accessdate=1 September 2017 |date=1 September 2017}}</ref>}}To which Judge Beddoe responded: {{quote|"That is as may be, but this isn't a court of religion, this is a secular court and it expects to be treated with respect. That isn't in breach of any religious principles I'm aware of."<ref name="“cetusnews">{{cite news |title=Muslim convert accused of preaching sharia law says he won't stand for any man....before getting to his feet when ordered by judge |url=http://www.cetusnews.com/news/Muslim-convert-accused-of-preaching-sharia-law-ordered-to-stand-up-for-a-judge-who-told-him---This-is-not-a-court-of-religion-.HyxzoPG7KZ.html|accessdate=2 September 2017 |date=2 September 2017}}</ref>}} McFarlane then proceeded to stand for Judge Beddoe while he was speaking and during the rest of the hearing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Judge orders Muslim convert to 'get up. This is not a court of religion' |url=http://metro.co.uk/2017/08/30/judge-orders-muslim-convert-to-get-up-this-is-not-a-court-of-religion-6888738/|accessdate=11 October 2017 |date=30 August 2017 |first=Richard |last=Hartley-Parkinson |website=Metro|location=UK}}</ref>
==Charity== In May 2017 Judge Beddoe was a lead walker at the London Legal Walk organised by London Legal Support Trust, which was designed to bring together leading criminal practitioners to raises funds for charities that provide life changing legal advice and representation to those in need.<ref name="“londonlegalsupporttrust.org.uk">{{cite news |title=London Legal Trust: Lead Walkers 2017 |url=http://www.londonlegalsupporttrust.org.uk/our-events/london-legal-walk-2017/lead-walkers-2017/ |accessdate=5 September 2017 |date=5 September 2017}}</ref> It was attended by leading criminal practitioners and professionals working in the criminal justice system, including [[John Thomas, Baron Thomas of Cwmgiedd|Lord Thomas]], the [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Lord Chief Justice]], [[Nicholas Hilliard (judge)|Nicholas Hilliard QC]], [[Recorder of London]], and [[Igor Judge, Baron Judge| Lord Igor Judge]], former [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales]].<ref name="“londonlegalsupporttrust.org.uk"/> In June 2006 Beddoe cycled in the London to Brighton [[British Heart Foundation]] cycle rally to raise money in memory of a member of his former chambers, Paul Morgan, who died in 2005 of [[heart disease]] at the age of 50.<ref name="“36BR">{{cite news |title=36 Bedford Row News |url=https://36bedfordrow.co.uk/new_news.php?news_type=-1 |accessdate=5 September 2017 |date=5 September 2017 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060822191021/https://36bedfordrow.co.uk/new_news.php?news_type=-1 |archivedate=22 August 2006 |df= }}</ref>
