{{multiple issues| {{POV|date=October 2015}} {{peacock|date=October 2015}} }} '''Wendy Priesnitz''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[alternative education]] and [[environmental movement|environmental]] advocate.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sims|first1=Kris|title=Back to home school|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2011/09/06/back-to-home-school|website=Toronto Sun|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Small Houses are Beautiful - Natural Life Magazine|url=http://www.life.ca/naturallife/0706/smallhouse.htm|website=www.life.ca|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref> She was leader of the [[Green Party of Canada]] from July 1996 to January 1997, when she abruptly resigned.
She is known for her advocacy of [[homeschooling]]/[[unschooling]] and [[home business|home-based]]/[[sustainable business|green business]]. Unschooling encourages students to use their curiosity to learn.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/taylor-butch/as-the-world-unfolds-a-se_b_10870580.html|title=As the World Unfolds: A Secret Look Inside Alternative Learning|last=Butch|first=Taylor|date=2016-07-08|website=Huffington Post|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref> She founded the Canadian Alliance of Home Schoolers in 1979, and is the author of numerous books on homeschooling. Since 1976, she has co-owned and edited ''Natural Life'', an award-winning sustainable lifestyles magazine. In 2002, she founded ''Life Learning Magazine'', which she owns and edits. She is listed in ''Canadian Who's Who'' and ''Who's Who of Canadian Women''.
